-- South African Stocks: BHP, Datatec, Freeworld, Gold Reef, Lonmin
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-12-13T16:11:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-13/anglo-bhp-lonmin-nampak-pioneer-south-african-equities.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  snapped two days of losses, climbing 76.37, or 0.2
percent, to 31,565.18 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s largest producer
of the metal, gained 3.32 rand, or 0.5 percent, to 684.99 rand,
the biggest jump in almost a week. Platinum increased as much as
1.3 percent.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-
largest producer, added 4.07 rand, or 1.9 percent, to 221 rand.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s biggest mining
company, snapped three days of losses, climbing 3.01 rand, or
1.1 percent, to 269.01 rand. Copper futures climbed to a 31-
month high in New York and a record in London after China
refrained from raising borrowing costs.  Datatec Ltd.  (DTC SJ), a networking technology and
computer-services company, advanced for the second day, adding
98 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 32.48 rand. Datatec said it
 purchased  a 30 percent equity stake in Cornwall Energy
Associates Ltd, a U.K.-based research and consulting business
focusing on electricity generation and distribution.  Freeworld Coatings Ltd.  (FWD SJ), a paint producer,
advanced 1.15 rand, or 11 percent, to 11.40 rand, the highest
since Sept. 30. Kansai Paint Co., which owns 27.6 percent of
Freeworld, offered to buy the remaining shares for 12 rand a
share.  Gold Reef Resorts Ltd.  (GDF SJ), a hotel and gaming
company, dropped for the first time in six days, losing 25
cents, or 1.3 percent, to 19 rand. The company said the
Competition Tribunal’s hearings into its merger with Tsogo
Investment Holding Co. will resume in January.  Lonmin Plc  (LON SJ), the world’s third-largest platinum
producer, gained 3.11 rand, or 1.6 percent, to 202.99 rand, the
highest since Nov. 15. The mining company is scheduled to resume
talks with the National Union of Mineworkers to resolve a wage
dispute.  Nampak Ltd.  (NPK SJ), the packaging company, rose to the
highest level since December 2007, gaining 75 cents, or 3.3
percent, to 23.2 rand. Nampak said it will sell its European
cartons and healthcare business to Maximus Holding II SARL and
use the estimated 65 million pounds ($102 million) in net
proceeds from the deal to reduce debt and invest in other
businesses.  To contact the reporter on this story:
